      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0664P0-06423'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0664P0_20040913_GCR_97' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Clause 185 [<span class="italic">Warrants</span>]:
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0664P0-06424'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0664P0_20040913_GCR_98' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <span class="member">Lord Skelmersdale</span> moved Amendment No. 270C:
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0664P0-06425'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0664P0_20040913_GCR_99' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Page 130, leave out lines 11 and 12 and insert "sheriff"
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0664P0-06426'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0664P0_20040913_GCR_100' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Lord said: The amendment refers entirely to the authorisation of the warrant in Scotland. It has been put to us by the Scottish Law Society that the power to grant warrants should extend to sheriffs only. The society says that often a Justice of the Peace will not be legally qualified&#x2014;as would be the case south of the border&#x2014;and may be unfamiliar with the criteria needed to grant such warrants. Given the few times that such warrants will be needed, the JPs will not be able to build up expertise. The warrants are for investigating serious matters, so it would seem to be fair that a warrant should be authorised by someone who is legally qualified. I beg to move.
      </p>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0664P0-06427'>
        <a name='S5LV0664P0_20040913_GCR_101'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/ms-patricia-hollis' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
